{"type":"message","id":"268c07e1","parentId":"87fc5c62","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:47:19.490Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_rjo0s3rsth4h_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 104532\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\n\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action would advance the goals.\r\n\r\nCurrent state:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 (architecture cross-analysis) are complete\r\n- CFI Analysis was completed last session (44.8% pure noise, 5.7% high CFI)\r\n- Pending: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe next logical step based on the pending actions is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would compare CFI-weighted prediction vs frequency baseline.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete action to take:\r\n\r\n1. The CFI_RESULTS.md shows that most frequency-invariants are noise (CFI=0) and only 5.7% have high CFI\r\n2. A CFI-weighted compression experiment would filter out the noise and use only causal invariants\r\n3. This is the natural next step\r\n\r\nI should design and potentially implement a CFI-weighted compression experiment. The key insight is:\r\n- Frequency-based compression uses all invariants equally\r\n- CFI-weighted compression would use only high-CFI invariants for prediction\r\n\r\nA concrete action would be to create a design document or experimental setup for this compression comparison. Let me create an experiment spec that outlines how to test CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline.\r\n\r\nLet me write up a concise experiment design that can be implemented.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis reveals that 94.3% of frequency-invariants are either noise (CFI=0) or weak signals (CFI<0.7). A CFI-weighted compression approach that filters these out should significantly outperform frequency-only baseline in next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate experiment specification for CFI-weighted compression comparison, defining the methodology, metrics, and success criteria for comparing CFI-filtered vs frequency-baseline prediction.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-only baseline by filtering out metaprogramming artifacts (CFI≈0) and focusing on true causal invariants (CFI≥0.7).\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Baseline: Frequency-Only Compression\r\n- Use ALL frequency-invariants regardless of CFI\r\n- Predict next pulse based on highest frequency patterns\r\n- Current approach (de facto)\r\n\r\n### Treatment: CFI-Weighted Compression  \r\n- Filter: keep only invariants with CFI ≥ 0.7\r\n- Apply frequency weighting within high-CFI subset only\r\n- Predict next pulse based on causal trajectory patterns\r\n\r\n### Metrics\r\n1. **Prediction Accuracy**: Did predicted next-pulse content match actual?\r\n2. **Compression Ratio**: tokens_out / tokens_in\r\n3. **Signal-to-Noise Ratio**: CFI-weighted vs frequency-only divergence\r\n4. **Convergence Rate**: Pulses to stable state\r\n\r\n### Implementation\r\n```\r\n1. Extract frequency-invariants from recent pulses (n=50)\r\n2. Compute CFI for each invariant\r\n3. Split into two buckets:\r\n   - freq-only: all invariants\r\n   - cfi-filtered: CFI >= 0.7 only\r\n4. Generate next-pulse predictions from each bucket\r\n5. Compare predictions against actual next pulse\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Expected Outcome\r\n- CFI-filtered will have lower compression ratio (fewer invariants)\r\n- CFI-filtered will have higher prediction accuracy (signal only)\r\n- Gap between them quantifies metaprogramming contamination\r\n\r\n## Status\r\n- [x] Design drafted\r\n- [ ] Implementation pending\r\n- [ ] Results to be recorded in CFI_RESULTS.md\r\n\"\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n`\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 0\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:45:58\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774363639487}}
